Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi's arrival in Paris comes just days after US President Donald Trump retracted his country's earlier commitment to the 2015 Paris climate accord, leaving the future of the international agreement in jeopardy.The visit also comes at a time when the European Union is facing a turbulent time following Britain's decision to exit the 28-nation bloc.But in a meeting with German Chancellor Angela Merkel in Berlin earlier this week, Modi stressed that for India "the cohesiveness of the EU is very important."Read: Opinion: Trump's betrayal of humankindIndia's environment minister Harsh Vardhan said Friday his country remained committed to the accord regardless of the position of other nations."As far as the Paris agreement is concerned our government is committed irrespective of the stand of anyone, anywhere in the world," Vardhan told reporters in a reference to Trump's withdrawal from the deal.Modi, whose country is the third-biggest emitter of greenhouse gases in the world, said in Russia on Friday that he would continue to back the deal.Strengthening tiesPrior to his visit to Paris, Modi hailed the victory of Emmanuel Macron in last month's French presidential election as an opportunity for India and France to boost ties. The two countries signed a strategic partnership agreement in 1998."Within a lot of uncertainty and instability where we don't know in which the world's great powers are going, it's important to show that the relationship between France and India is stable," a senior French diplomat was quoted as saying by the Reuters news agency.Read: Putin on climate deal: 'Don't worry, be happy'Apart from a steady trade partnership, defense ties between the two countries have also expanded in recent years, with New Delhi ordering 36 French-made Rafale fighter jets to modernize its air force.France and India are also negotiating over nuclear power and renewable energy deals, but these are not expected to be sealed during Modi's current visit. Send Facebook Twitter Google+ Whatsapp Tumblr linkedin stumble Digg reddit Newsvine Permalink http://p.dw.com/p/2droQshs/jlw (Reuters, AP, AFP)